1
00:00:02,236 --> 00:00:03,871
It's kind of depressing...

2
00:00:04,037 --> 00:00:07,341
when your day ends just as the
sun has begun rising, isn't it?

3
00:00:07,541 --> 00:00:10,711
I know this is the fate of a bar hostess,
but it's not healthy.

4
00:00:10,978 --> 00:00:11,778
Really?

5
00:00:11,912 --> 00:00:13,614
I actually think it's pretty nice...

6
00:00:13,614 --> 00:00:15,449
While's the sun is down
we become the stars

7
00:00:15,449 --> 00:00:17,417
that light up the darkness
of the night.

8
00:00:17,851 --> 00:00:22,155
Besides, Bargain Dash ice cream
tastes so good after hard work!

9
00:00:22,289 --> 00:00:25,459
Otae, I really envy how easy
going you always are.

10
00:00:25,459 --> 00:00:26,693
I can't take it anymore.

11
00:00:26,693 --> 00:00:30,397
Some samurai named Sakamoto was
all over my butt again tonight.

12
00:00:30,397 --> 00:00:33,200
Honestly, just get used to it, Oryo.

13
00:00:33,333 --> 00:00:36,036
I also told you to break their fingers
whenever they try to do that.

14
00:00:36,036 --> 00:00:37,638
You're actually breaking fingers?

15
00:00:37,638 --> 00:00:39,039
I thought we're the stars?

16
00:00:39,039 --> 00:00:40,474
You're more like a black hole!

17
00:00:40,474 --> 00:00:43,810
If only the new girl, Hanako,
could be as tough as you are.

18
00:00:44,044 --> 00:00:45,979
She took off from work today, too.

19
00:00:46,179 --> 00:00:47,447
I wonder what's wrong.

20
00:00:47,614 --> 00:00:48,549
Who knows?

21
00:00:48,549 --> 00:00:50,651
It's not all that unusual
in our line of work.

22
00:00:50,751 --> 00:00:51,885
It's a pretty tough job.

23
00:00:54,888 --> 00:00:56,189
Isn't that Hanako?

24
00:00:56,356 --> 00:00:58,125
I wonder what she's doing over there.

25
00:01:01,895 --> 00:01:02,629
Hey!

26
00:01:02,629 --> 00:01:04,031
What are you doing, Hanaako?

27
00:01:04,298 --> 00:01:05,999
D‐Don't come any closer!

28
00:01:06,266 --> 00:01:07,467
Hanako, don't!

29
00:01:07,467 --> 00:01:08,568
You aren't.

30
00:01:09,002 --> 00:01:12,272
I was wondering what you were doing,
taking time off work, but this...

31
00:01:12,539 --> 00:01:15,175
If you want to catch crayfish,
you need to find a shallow river!

32
00:01:15,342 --> 00:01:16,476
What are you talking about!

33
00:01:16,476 --> 00:01:18,111
Look at this situation, would you!

34
00:01:18,111 --> 00:01:19,780
I just can't take it anymore.

35
00:01:19,780 --> 00:01:21,281
I've had enough.
It's over...

36
00:01:21,281 --> 00:01:22,583
Goodbye!

37
00:01:22,583 --> 00:01:23,817
Look out!!

38
00:01:31,058 --> 00:01:31,925
That was dangerous.

39
00:01:31,925 --> 00:01:34,194
You're the one that's
really dangerous!

40
00:03:08,488 --> 00:03:10,157
My sister sure is late.

41
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:13,293
And after I prepared a hotpot
now that I finally got paid.

42
00:03:13,593 --> 00:03:16,563
She's probably spending time with
one of her customers after work.

43
00:03:16,697 --> 00:03:17,964
The hotpot is ready.

44
00:03:18,865 --> 00:03:20,400
Hey, what did you put in there?

45
00:03:20,634 --> 00:03:21,701
It looks really dangerous,

46
00:03:21,701 --> 00:03:24,204
like an evil witch's
bubbling cauldron.

47
00:03:24,371 --> 00:03:25,572
I went ahead and
threw everything

48
00:03:25,572 --> 00:03:27,607
that was in the
refridgerator in here.

49
00:03:27,808 --> 00:03:30,444
Hotpots taste better the larger
the variety of ingredients.

50
00:03:30,710 --> 00:03:32,045
How's it taste, Kagura?

51
00:03:32,712 --> 00:03:35,082
I think it tastes like
the bottom of your feet.

52
00:03:35,248 --> 00:03:37,084
Hey, hey, that's not good.

53
00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:38,318
You've got WMD!

54
00:03:38,318 --> 00:03:40,053
That's your own feet
you're talking about.

55
00:03:40,053 --> 00:03:41,822
Now what are you going
to do about this?

56
00:03:41,988 --> 00:03:43,957
I suppose I could try taking
more showers.

57
00:03:43,957 --> 00:03:45,392
I'm not talking about your feet!

58
00:03:45,392 --> 00:03:46,460
I'm talking about the hotpot!

59
00:03:46,460 --> 00:03:47,627
I'm home.

60
00:03:48,395 --> 00:03:49,096
Oh no.

61
00:03:49,096 --> 00:03:49,996
She's back.

62
00:03:49,996 --> 00:03:51,031
‐Sis is back...
‐Do we have any

63
00:03:51,031 --> 00:03:53,300
ingredients left that can
save this thing?

64
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:54,101
That's it!

65
00:03:54,101 --> 00:03:55,469
‐I'll put my feet in inside it!
‐She is back.

66
00:03:55,702 --> 00:03:56,803
That should fix it!.

67
00:03:57,037 --> 00:03:58,572
Two negatives make
a positive, right?

68
00:03:59,272 --> 00:03:59,973
‐Hm?
‐Hm?

69
00:04:00,173 --> 00:04:02,209
Kagura, what are you
putting in there?

70
00:04:02,309 --> 00:04:03,610
It's Bargain‐Dash ice cream.

71
00:04:03,944 --> 00:04:06,446
Big sis said she loves
Bargain‐Dash ice cream,

72
00:04:06,446 --> 00:04:08,448
so she's bound to love this.

73
00:04:08,582 --> 00:04:10,650
Kagura, listen, you may as well.

74
00:04:10,650 --> 00:04:13,320
just be flushing that ice cream
down the toilet.

75
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:14,921
Let's clean up.

76
00:04:14,921 --> 00:04:16,289
It's better if we get rid of this!

77
00:04:16,289 --> 00:04:17,858
Destroy all the evidence!

78
00:04:18,058 --> 00:04:18,925
Stop that.

79
00:04:19,192 --> 00:04:20,160
Don't give up.

80
00:04:20,327 --> 00:04:22,262
‐It's only game over when we give up!!
<i>‐Hey, Shinpachi,</i>

81
00:04:22,262 --> 00:04:24,064
<i>have you seen my</i>
<i>Bargain‐Dash?</i>

82
00:04:24,064 --> 00:04:25,265
<i>I had it in the freezer.</i>

83
00:04:25,899 --> 00:04:26,633
This is bad.

84
00:04:26,633 --> 00:04:29,402
She's already noticed that the
Bargain‐Dash ice cream is missing.

85
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:30,837
Where's the ladle?!

86
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:32,005
‐It's hot hot hot...
‐Forget it!

87
00:04:32,005 --> 00:04:33,573
‐It already melted away.
‐It's burning!

88
00:04:40,780 --> 00:04:41,915
<i>How can I help you?</i>

89
00:04:42,449 --> 00:04:43,416
‐One hundred cups of
‐One hundred cups of

90
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:44,618
‐Bargain‐Dash, please.
‐Bargain‐Dash, please.

91
00:04:44,618 --> 00:04:45,785
Okay, sirs, you do know,

92
00:04:45,785 --> 00:04:48,088
even if you collect a hundred
cups of Bargain‐Dash,

93
00:04:48,088 --> 00:04:50,290
your wishes won't magically
come true.

94
00:04:50,423 --> 00:04:53,160
Just bring me a hundred cups
already, baldy.

95
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:55,629
I'm so sorry.

96
00:04:55,629 --> 00:04:57,030
I wanted to cheer
you up with some

97
00:04:57,030 --> 00:04:59,299
Bargain‐Dash ice cream,
but I'm afraid...

98
00:04:59,299 --> 00:05:00,934
I did my best to
stop them, Big sis,

99
00:05:01,168 --> 00:05:03,036
but they're a really
hopeless bunch.

100
00:05:03,370 --> 00:05:05,038
Well, at least we have
a hotpot going.

101
00:05:05,272 --> 00:05:07,073
Hanako, dear,
help yourself to some.

102
00:05:07,240 --> 00:05:08,175
Oh...

103
00:05:08,975 --> 00:05:09,976
Oh wait.

104
00:05:10,076 --> 00:05:11,478
You don't like hotpots?

105
00:05:11,645 --> 00:05:13,980
You came here from Osaka,
didn't you?

106
00:05:14,414 --> 00:05:16,349
Would you prefer Osaka
style cuisine instead?

107
00:05:16,516 --> 00:05:17,584
Old Sucker?

108
00:05:17,584 --> 00:05:18,785
Are you a migrant worker?

109
00:05:18,785 --> 00:05:19,619
Me too.

110
00:05:19,619 --> 00:05:20,720
We're alike.

111
00:05:21,855 --> 00:05:22,989
Hanako...

112
00:05:23,123 --> 00:05:24,257
Oh no, I'm sorry.

113
00:05:24,524 --> 00:05:26,259
Ever since I came to Edo City,

114
00:05:26,259 --> 00:05:28,828
I haven't experienced the kindness
of others like this.

115
00:05:29,229 --> 00:05:32,766
I never knew such a kind person
like you existed here.

116
00:05:33,433 --> 00:05:34,501
My dear Hanako...

117
00:05:34,668 --> 00:05:36,069
Old Sucker, what's wrong with you?

118
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:37,537
Cheer up!
Have a drink!

119
00:05:37,537 --> 00:05:38,905
Drinking makes everything better!

120
00:05:38,905 --> 00:05:40,840
Don't let the city get the best of you!

121
00:05:41,374 --> 00:05:44,211
<i>Hanako, listen you can</i>
<i>tell me what's wrong.</i>

122
00:05:45,078 --> 00:05:48,348
I would like to do what every
is possible to help you out.

123
00:05:48,548 --> 00:05:51,518
We both live in similar circumstances,
after all.

124
00:05:52,519 --> 00:05:53,820
Otae, wow...

125
00:05:54,521 --> 00:05:55,455
Really?

126
00:05:55,622 --> 00:05:57,691
Are you really going
to help me out?

127
00:05:57,857 --> 00:05:58,592
Sure.

128
00:05:58,592 --> 00:05:59,893
If there's anything I can do.

129
00:06:00,093 --> 00:06:01,661
Umm, in that case...

130
00:06:02,095 --> 00:06:03,530
This is difficult to say,
but will you.

131
00:06:03,530 --> 00:06:05,532
I won't lend you any money.

132
00:06:07,767 --> 00:06:08,935
Of course not.

133
00:06:08,935 --> 00:06:11,871
But will, will you listen to my story?

134
00:06:15,108 --> 00:06:16,176
Dream catcher?

135
00:06:16,176 --> 00:06:17,077
That's right.

136
00:06:17,244 --> 00:06:19,012
I fell for something pretty nasty.

137
00:06:19,512 --> 00:06:23,116
I came to Edo City to fulfill my
dream of becoming a dancer...

138
00:06:23,917 --> 00:06:27,120
but they seized all the money
I'd saved up for my dream.

139
00:06:27,420 --> 00:06:28,888
What do you mean Hanako?

140
00:06:28,888 --> 00:06:30,190
I was tricked!

141
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:32,626
They took advantage
of my weakness.

142
00:06:33,860 --> 00:06:34,661
<i>Oh?</i>

143
00:06:34,661 --> 00:06:36,463
So you want to become a dancer.

144
00:06:36,596 --> 00:06:38,164
So that's why you're
saving up your earnings

145
00:06:38,164 --> 00:06:39,532
working as a waitress.

146
00:06:39,532 --> 00:06:40,767
That's very admirable.

147
00:06:41,001 --> 00:06:42,602
I never knew there were
such respectable youths

148
00:06:42,602 --> 00:06:43,703
in this day and age.

149
00:06:43,703 --> 00:06:46,006
Yes but, you aren't
able to achieve

150
00:06:46,006 --> 00:06:47,941
your dream with just ambition.

151
00:06:47,941 --> 00:06:50,210
If you could, then the
world would be filled

152
00:06:50,210 --> 00:06:53,880
with pilots and baseball players
and other winners as well.

153
00:06:53,980 --> 00:06:56,283
Ambition is the power
to pursue your dreams.

154
00:06:56,416 --> 00:06:57,250
But you need another power

155
00:06:57,250 --> 00:06:59,185
in order to reach the
unreachable dream.

156
00:06:59,319 --> 00:07:02,022
We call this incredible power
a dream catcher,

157
00:07:02,022 --> 00:07:04,224
have you ever heard of it?
Have you?

158
00:07:04,824 --> 00:07:06,192
A dream catcher?

159
00:07:06,326 --> 00:07:07,360
That's right.

160
00:07:07,494 --> 00:07:09,829
Most people would say that you
either have the power

161
00:07:09,829 --> 00:07:11,364
to catch dreams or you don't.

162
00:07:11,598 --> 00:07:14,701
That some people are born with
it and others are born without.

163
00:07:14,801 --> 00:07:17,137
But the Dream Faith shows us
how to overcome

164
00:07:17,137 --> 00:07:19,539
our innate handicaps in
order to achieve our dreams

165
00:07:19,539 --> 00:07:21,107
and make everyone happy.

166
00:07:21,641 --> 00:07:23,677
Do you know the one
thing that people

167
00:07:23,677 --> 00:07:26,880
who achieve their dreams in this
world all have in common?

168
00:07:27,247 --> 00:07:28,548
Tell me, do you?

169
00:07:28,948 --> 00:07:32,185
Julius Caesar, Napoleon,
the soccer player Donaldo,

170
00:07:32,185 --> 00:07:35,722
and the baseball player Chichiro
were all born with this power.

171
00:07:36,022 --> 00:07:37,324
And while we were not,

172
00:07:37,324 --> 00:07:40,460
we have succeeded
in producing it artificially.

173
00:07:41,428 --> 00:07:42,729
And here...

174
00:07:42,729 --> 00:07:44,097
it is!

175
00:07:59,245 --> 00:08:00,480
What is that thing?

176
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:02,148
They said that all of the people

177
00:08:02,148 --> 00:08:03,283
who achieved their dreams

178
00:08:03,283 --> 00:08:06,052
had a mole with a hair growing
out of it on their body.

179
00:08:06,152 --> 00:08:08,922
I spent a whole lot of money
for this stick‐on mole.

180
00:08:08,922 --> 00:08:10,657
But nothing at all happened...

181
00:08:10,657 --> 00:08:12,659
I was completely duped.

182
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:15,495
Are you totally stupid or what?

183
00:08:15,729 --> 00:08:18,298
Are you going to let that tiny
bean dictate your life?

184
00:08:18,798 --> 00:08:20,367
Were you planning on
dancing on the stage

185
00:08:20,367 --> 00:08:21,868
with that dirty‐looking
mole on your face?

186
00:08:21,868 --> 00:08:23,403
‐A hair growing mole
‐Come on, Old Sucker!

187
00:08:23,403 --> 00:08:25,438
‐on a dancer?!
‐Get up from the bottom of the pit!

188
00:08:27,941 --> 00:08:28,942
So now tell me...

189
00:08:29,175 --> 00:08:30,310
What else happened to you?

190
00:08:30,310 --> 00:08:31,044
There, there.

191
00:08:31,044 --> 00:08:32,879
You did great, old sucker.

192
00:08:32,879 --> 00:08:35,181
Next time, let's try
for thirty‐seconds.

193
00:08:35,382 --> 00:08:37,917
I was forced to convert to
the Dream Faith Cult.

194
00:08:38,218 --> 00:08:40,920
Also, I couldn't turn down
newspaper salesmen,

195
00:08:40,920 --> 00:08:43,456
so I ended up subscribing
to nine newspapers,

196
00:08:43,456 --> 00:08:45,592
and I bought 20 fire
extinguishers.

197
00:08:45,592 --> 00:08:47,093
Edo City is so scary!

198
00:08:47,093 --> 00:08:50,597
I just can't survive this
concrete jungle, I can't do it!

199
00:08:50,730 --> 00:08:54,000
You wouldn't be able to survive in a
jungle filled with nothing but sloths.

200
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,102
Osaka is a heart‐warming town.

201
00:08:56,302 --> 00:08:58,304
Naturally, there are
bad‐tempered people,

202
00:08:58,304 --> 00:09:00,206
but everyone has a
certain warm spirit

203
00:09:00,206 --> 00:09:01,641
you'd never expect
from a stranger.

204
00:09:01,808 --> 00:09:03,810
But everyone in Edo City is so cold.

205
00:09:03,810 --> 00:09:05,912
People treat each other like strangers.

206
00:09:06,146 --> 00:09:08,615
I just...
I don't think I can get by here.

207
00:09:09,349 --> 00:09:12,485
If you're suffering that badly, then
shouldn't you just go back home?

208
00:09:12,752 --> 00:09:14,788
After all, you can dance anywhere,
you know...

209
00:09:15,422 --> 00:09:17,357
As long as you keep
depending on others,

210
00:09:17,524 --> 00:09:18,925
I didn't think you'll get
very far in life

211
00:09:18,925 --> 00:09:20,160
no matter where you go.

212
00:09:20,660 --> 00:09:21,561
But...

213
00:09:21,561 --> 00:09:24,297
If you still want to pursue your dream
of becoming a dancer

214
00:09:24,297 --> 00:09:26,199
in Edo City, then I'll help you out.

215
00:09:26,433 --> 00:09:28,868
The Capital has its own way
of showing compassion.

216
00:09:29,335 --> 00:09:30,236
Right...

217
00:09:30,303 --> 00:09:31,204
Gintoki ?

218
00:09:42,148 --> 00:09:43,383
Fellow believers!

219
00:09:43,550 --> 00:09:44,651
Do you have a dream?

220
00:09:44,651 --> 00:09:46,419
<i>We dream like crazy!</i>

221
00:09:46,519 --> 00:09:49,422
And are you running towards
your dreams?

222
00:09:49,422 --> 00:09:51,458
<i>We run like crazy!</i>

223
00:09:51,458 --> 00:09:55,628
Well, everyone, what a joy it is
to see you all so full of faith!

224
00:09:55,628 --> 00:09:57,597
If you continue chasing
your dreams here,

225
00:09:57,597 --> 00:10:00,333
you might be able to catch
those dreams pretty soon.

226
00:10:00,767 --> 00:10:04,070
So today, Hanako, who dreams
of becoming a dancer,

227
00:10:04,070 --> 00:10:06,706
has brought us some
new dream chasers.

228
00:10:06,973 --> 00:10:08,675
Let me introduce them to you all.

229
00:10:09,108 --> 00:10:10,143
Hello there, guys!

230
00:10:10,143 --> 00:10:11,845
Do you all have dreams?!

231
00:10:11,845 --> 00:10:13,746
<i>‐We dream like crazy!</i>
<i>‐We dream like crazy!</i>

232
00:10:14,514 --> 00:10:17,717
Otae Shimura, now tell us,
what is your dream?

233
00:10:17,984 --> 00:10:19,085
My father's dojo.

234
00:10:19,085 --> 00:10:20,520
I would like to rebuild it.

235
00:10:20,520 --> 00:10:23,690
Hanako, dear, we all know
that your dream is to...?

236
00:10:23,823 --> 00:10:25,925
To get my money back from
a phony relig...

237
00:10:26,392 --> 00:10:28,728
<i>My dream is to eat</i>
<i>a giant bowl of rice</i>

238
00:10:28,728 --> 00:10:31,664
<i>that has been covered with a</i>
<i>whole jar of seaweed jam.</i>

239
00:10:31,831 --> 00:10:32,899
<i>But if it comes true,</i>

240
00:10:32,899 --> 00:10:34,934
<i>I won't have anything</i>
<i>else to dream about,</i>

241
00:10:34,934 --> 00:10:36,135
<i>so I'll keep it to myself!</i>

242
00:10:36,135 --> 00:10:37,437
Is that so?

243
00:10:37,737 --> 00:10:38,805
And you...

244
00:10:39,439 --> 00:10:42,442
you probably just want better
eyesight or something boring.

245
00:10:42,542 --> 00:10:44,110
Hey!
At least ask me!

246
00:10:44,777 --> 00:10:46,346
And what is your dream?

247
00:10:46,346 --> 00:10:47,313
My dream?

248
00:10:47,447 --> 00:10:50,216
The thing is, I've misplaced that
a long time ago already.

249
00:10:50,950 --> 00:10:52,318
Then what did you
come here to do?

250
00:10:52,318 --> 00:10:55,021
Look, I just don't have what
I just don't have, okay?

251
00:10:55,188 --> 00:10:58,191
How about "I want silky straight hair,
or something like that?"

252
00:10:58,691 --> 00:11:00,093
Sure, I'll go with that, then.

